In the figure, $\angle EAB$ and $\angle ABC$ are right angles, $AB=4,$ $BC=6,$ $AE=8,$ and $\overline{AC}$ and $\overline{BE}$ intersect at $D.$ What is the difference between the areas of $\triangle ADE$ and $\triangle BDC?$ [asy]
pair A,B,C,D,I;
I=(0,8);
A=(0,0);
B=(4,0);
C=(4,6);
D=(2.5,4);
draw(A--B--I--cycle,linewidth(0.7));
draw(A--B--C--cycle,linewidth(0.7));
label("$E$",I,N);
label("$C$",C,N);
label("$D$",D,N);
label("$A$",A,S);
label("$B$",B,S);
label("8",(0,4),W);
label("6",(4,3),E);
label("4",(2,0),S);
[/asy]

inference:
Solution:

The area of $\triangle ADE$ is $\frac{1}{2}(AE)(AD)=\frac{1}{2}(8)(AD)=4AD.$  The area of $\triangle BDC$ is $\frac{1}{2}(BC)(BD)=\frac{1}{2}(6)(BD)=3BD.$

[asy]
pair A,B,C,D,I;
I=(0,8);
A=(0,0);
B=(4,0);
C=(4,6);
D=(2.5,4);
draw(A--B--I--cycle,linewidth(0.7));
draw(A--B--C--cycle,linewidth(0.7));
label("$E$",I,N);
label("$C$",C,N);
label("$D$",D,N);
label("$A$",A,S);
label("$B$",B,S);
label("8",(0,4),W);
label("6",(4,3),E);
label("4",(2,0),S);
draw(rightanglemark(A,B,I,10));
draw(rightanglemark(B,A,C,10));
draw(A--D,dashed);
draw(B--D,dashed);
label("$AD$",(A+D)/2,NW);
label("$BD$",(B+D)/2,SE);
[/asy]

Since $\triangle ADE$ and $\triangle BDC$ share the same altitude from $D$, the ratio of their areas is equal to the ratio of their bases. Therefore $\frac{4AD}{3BD}=\frac{AD}{BD}=\frac{AE}{BC}=\frac{8}{6}=\frac{4}{3}$.  Hence, $4AD=\frac{16}{3}BD$ and the difference between the areas of $\triangle ADE$ and $\triangle BDC$ is $\frac{16}{3}BD-3BD=\boxed{\frac{7}{3}BD}$. I hope it is correct.

